> Attribution is disputed: Trader Vic is sometimes credited (1950s), but Beachbum Berry's research traces the drink back to Don the Beachcomber — originally a Cuban-rum spec on a postcard, later adjusted post-embargo.[^1] Both bars served versions; what follows is Berry's Donn Beach reconstruction.[^2] The authentic presentation is in a hollowed-out small pineapple. Fassionola brand matters here too — Jonathan English Hibiscus Hurricane or BG Reynolds give the intended profile, and pomegranate grenadine is an acceptable substitute when neither is on hand.
>
> Brand recommendations. Best: Don Q Anejo or Bacardi 8 for the gold Puerto Rican, Smith & Cross or Hamilton Pot Still Black for the dark Jamaican, BG Reynolds Fassionola, Velvet Falernum (Velier), Funkin or Perfect Puree passion fruit. Economical: Bacardi Gold for the Puerto Rican, Coruba or Appleton Signature for the Jamaican, Yacht Club Fassionola, John D. Taylor's Velvet Falernum, Ceres or Goya passion fruit nectar.

Add @fresh lime juice{0.75%oz}, @passion fruit juice{1%oz}, @pineapple juice{3%oz}, @rich honey syrup{0.5%oz}, @falernum{1%dash}, @Angostura bitters{2%dashes}, @fassionola{0.5%oz}, @gold Puerto Rican rum{1%oz}, and @dark Jamaican rum{1%oz} to a #blender{}.

> Honey cream mix may be used in place of rich honey syrup.

Add 6 oz of crushed ice and flash blend at high speed for no more than 5 seconds.

Pour unstrained into a hollowed-out @small pineapple{1} (traditional) or large #tiki mug{}.

Garnish with a @mint sprig{1}.

> [^1]: Berry, *Beachbum Berry Remixed* (2010), Pi-Yi entry — traces the drink to Don the Beachcomber via a postcard-era Cuban-rum spec and notes both bars served versions; the source for this file's reconstruction.
> [^2]: "Pi-Yi." Vintage American Cocktails. https://vintageamericancocktails.com/pi-yi/ (accessed 2026-05-03) — published spec following Berry's Remixed reconstruction; the source for this file's measurement bill.
